16
00:01:20,354 --> 00:01:22,022
ROSE: That's everything.
Thank you, Stewart.

17
00:01:22,106 --> 00:01:23,441
MIDGE: Yes, thanks, guys.

18
00:01:23,525 --> 00:01:25,443
Once again, you're our heroes.

19
00:01:25,527 --> 00:01:27,237
Ah, the ever elusive cabana jackets.

20
00:01:27,321 --> 00:01:28,863
How many should we bring?

21
00:01:28,947 --> 00:01:30,323
-Two each.
-Or three.

22
00:01:30,407 --> 00:01:32,075
I've got one more coming from Saks.

23
00:01:32,159 --> 00:01:33,661
It's chinoiserie. You're gonna love it.

24
00:01:33,745 --> 00:01:35,162
Ooh. Bikinis.

25
00:01:35,246 --> 00:01:37,081
You're doing the beauty
contest again, I assume.

26
00:01:37,165 --> 00:01:39,083
I believe my public demands it.

27
00:01:39,167 --> 00:01:41,920
So this year, should I go classy?

28
00:01:42,004 --> 00:01:43,129
Your Doris Day.

29
00:01:43,213 --> 00:01:45,173
-Or risqué?
-Your Mamie Van Doren.

30
00:01:45,257 --> 00:01:46,967
Will any other girl bother to compete?

31
00:01:47,051 --> 00:01:48,093
I wouldn't.

32
00:01:48,177 --> 00:01:49,469
Bring them both, just to be sure.

33
00:01:49,553 --> 00:01:50,846
ABE: You can't bring everything!

34
00:01:50,930 --> 00:01:52,473
Next is clamdiggers.

35
00:01:52,557 --> 00:01:54,183
It's the Catskills; you can't
have too many clamdiggers.

36
00:01:54,267 --> 00:01:55,685
ABE: Yes, you can.

37
00:01:55,769 --> 00:01:57,395
What about picnic dresses?
We each have four.

38
00:01:57,479 --> 00:01:59,397
-Should I bring them all?
-There may be four picnics.

39
00:01:59,481 --> 00:02:02,901
Or you can wear the same picnic
dress to more than one picnic.

40
00:02:02,985 --> 00:02:05,904
-Oh, Abe.
-[LAUGHS] Papa, you're too much.

41
00:02:05,988 --> 00:02:07,781
Ladies, we've been over this.

42
00:02:07,865 --> 00:02:11,035
The trailer has 163 cubic feet of space.

43
00:02:11,119 --> 00:02:13,162
Do you understand?
There's finite capacity.

44
00:02:13,246 --> 00:02:14,414
-Beach robes?
-We never wear them.

45
00:02:14,498 --> 00:02:15,832
-I'll bring them anyway.
-Okay.

46
00:02:15,916 --> 00:02:17,417
D… Did you see what just happened there?

47
00:02:17,501 --> 00:02:19,252
Papa, please do not micromanage this.
We have a system.

48
00:02:19,336 --> 00:02:21,130
Your system is to bring
everything you own.

49
00:02:21,214 --> 00:02:22,882
I'm not bringing this.

50
00:02:22,966 --> 00:02:25,175
It's too late to change
the luggage we've chosen.

51
00:02:25,259 --> 00:02:26,760
I've made precisely scaled models.

52
00:02:26,844 --> 00:02:28,178
Your little toys.

53
00:02:28,262 --> 00:02:29,513
-They're not toys.
-They're cute.

54
00:02:29,597 --> 00:02:31,516
They're cute, yes, but they're not toys.

55
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:33,602
And right now, after much effort,

56
00:02:33,686 --> 00:02:35,896
all our tiny luggage
fits in our tiny trailer.

57
00:02:35,980 --> 00:02:38,189
He's adorable when he
talks about these things.

58
00:02:38,273 --> 00:02:41,068
Papa, we will do our best
to stick to 160 cubic feet.

59
00:02:41,152 --> 00:02:42,278
-I promise.
-Good.

60
00:02:42,362 --> 00:02:43,988
This way, I can create a plan

61
00:02:44,072 --> 00:02:45,865
so that my boy Jimmy at the resort knows

62
00:02:45,949 --> 00:02:48,200
how to load it back up
at the end of our stay.

63
00:02:48,284 --> 00:02:49,745
You got Jimmy as your
boy again this year?

64
00:02:49,829 --> 00:02:51,163
I thought he couldn't come back.

65
00:02:51,247 --> 00:02:53,624
Yeah, he thought he was doing
an internship at a big law firm,

66
00:02:53,708 --> 00:02:56,084
but I made a couple of
calls, and now he's not.

67
00:02:56,168 --> 00:02:58,045
Abe, you did not spoil
that young man's future

68
00:02:58,129 --> 00:02:59,964
just so he can be your
boy again in the Catskills.

69
00:03:00,048 --> 00:03:01,716
What? No.

70
00:03:01,800 --> 00:03:04,093
I called and found out he didn't get it.

71
00:03:04,177 --> 00:03:05,678
I was heartbroken for him.

72
00:03:05,762 --> 00:03:07,805
I wouldn't do that to Jimmy.
I love Jimmy.

73
00:03:07,889 --> 00:03:09,308
-Mm-hmm.
-A little too much.

74
00:03:09,392 --> 00:03:11,602
-Scale down, please.
-We're scaling. Go.

75
00:03:11,686 --> 00:03:13,520
-Yes, go, Abe.
-I'm supposed to have lunch with a friend.

76
00:03:13,604 --> 00:03:15,481
-Okay if I scoot?
-ABE: Ethan, no!

77
00:03:15,565 --> 00:03:18,233
-Do not play with these toys.
-Sure, go. We'll finish later.

78
00:03:18,317 --> 00:03:20,236
ABE: I didn't mean toys.
They're not toys.

79
00:03:20,320 --> 00:03:22,280
-I won't be long. Thank you, Zelda.
-ABE: It was a misnomer.

80
00:03:22,364 --> 00:03:24,115
You know what a misnomer is.

81
00:03:24,199 --> 00:03:25,617
No, no. Don't play dumb.

82
00:03:25,701 --> 00:03:27,285
These club owners
call me back in a flash.

83
00:03:27,369 --> 00:03:28,955
Sometimes I hear 'em
yell, "Take a message,"

84
00:03:29,039 --> 00:03:31,165
and when they hear it's me
on the phone, they take the call.

85
00:03:31,249 --> 00:03:33,084
-That's respect.
-For me. I mean, look at me.

86
00:03:33,168 --> 00:03:34,794
-They're respecting me.
-I'm looking at you.

87
00:03:34,878 --> 00:03:37,546
Alone, I am a spittoon;
with you, I'm a somebody.

88
00:03:37,630 --> 00:03:39,257
That's not true, Susie. They respect you

89
00:03:39,341 --> 00:03:41,760
because they fear you;
you're great at what you do.

90
00:03:41,844 --> 00:03:43,011
Mm, half of them respect me, maybe.

91
00:03:43,095 --> 00:03:44,680
The other half want to get in your pants.

92
00:03:44,764 --> 00:03:47,849
-Oh, stop.
-It's gonna happen. I mean, look at you.

93
00:03:47,933 --> 00:03:49,644
It's like a dollop of
whipped cream grew a head.

94
00:03:49,728 --> 00:03:51,980
Just don't undercut
yourself; that's all I'm saying.

95
00:03:52,064 --> 00:03:54,232
So you called this lunch.
What do you want to talk about?

96
00:03:54,316 --> 00:03:56,150
I just wanted to touch base
before I go to the Catskills.

97
00:03:56,234 --> 00:03:57,610
-We leave tomorrow.
-Cool.

98
00:03:57,694 --> 00:03:59,279
God, it's gonna be so
nice to have a break.

99
00:03:59,363 --> 00:04:01,365
This past year has been tough.
They're leaving.

100
00:04:01,449 --> 00:04:02,450
Hurry, hurry.

101
00:04:04,077 --> 00:04:07,287
We're switching tables, Verla!

102
00:04:07,371 --> 00:04:09,457
Oh, here.

103
00:04:09,541 --> 00:04:11,084
-What's this?
-Gigs.

104
00:04:11,168 --> 00:04:12,585
My typewriter lost its "S."

105
00:04:12,669 --> 00:04:14,587
That's why it says "Aturday," "Unday."

106
00:04:14,671 --> 00:04:16,381
You went to college;
you can figure it out.

107
00:04:16,465 --> 00:04:18,050
These are all in the next two weeks.

108
00:04:18,134 --> 00:04:20,302
-So?
-I'm going to the Catskills.

109
00:04:20,386 --> 00:04:22,013
-Yeah, you said.
-So I can't do these.

110
00:04:22,097 --> 00:04:23,389
I'm going to the Catskills.

111
00:04:23,473 --> 00:04:25,099
First one's not till a week after next.

112
00:04:25,183 --> 00:04:26,600
But I'm going to the Catskills.

113
00:04:26,684 --> 00:04:28,478
Yeah, your record's skippin', missy.
Get to the point.

114
00:04:28,562 --> 00:04:30,230
I'm going to the
Catskills for two months.

115
00:04:30,314 --> 00:04:33,150
-Wha…
-Geez, I almost did a spit take.

116
00:04:33,234 --> 00:04:35,610
Almost? That was a fucking spit take.

117
00:04:35,694 --> 00:04:37,572
You're going to the
Catskills for two months?

118
00:04:37,656 --> 00:04:40,074
I told you a million times I
was going to the Catskills.

119
00:04:40,158 --> 00:04:41,951
Yeah, but I figured
it was five days, tops,

120
00:04:42,035 --> 00:04:43,453
not two fucking months.

121
00:04:43,537 --> 00:04:45,163
I think you got the
guy in back of me, too.

122
00:04:45,247 --> 00:04:46,957
What the hell do you do
up there for two months?

123
00:04:47,041 --> 00:04:48,959
-Lots of things.
-What things?

124
00:04:49,043 --> 00:04:50,544
You look at a tree, you go to bed,

125
00:04:50,628 --> 00:04:51,920
you get up, you look at a tree.

126
00:04:52,004 --> 00:04:53,255
You gonna do that for
two straight months?

127
00:04:53,339 --> 00:04:54,548
What the fuck is going on up there?

128
00:04:54,632 --> 00:04:56,843
There's activities.
We go boating, we sunbathe.

129
00:04:56,927 --> 00:04:58,553
What do you do for the summer?

130
00:04:58,637 --> 00:05:01,890
I stay here. And I sweat.
And I smell like a bum.

131
00:05:01,974 --> 00:05:03,558
And I'm miserable,
and I want to kill people.

132
00:05:03,642 --> 00:05:04,976
And I do that till it gets cold.

133
00:05:05,060 --> 00:05:06,812
But the whole city empties out in summer.

134
00:05:06,896 --> 00:05:08,939
Why the hell are we having
lunch if not to figure out

135
00:05:09,023 --> 00:05:10,608
our game plan for the next two months?

136
00:05:10,692 --> 00:05:13,360
I don't know, I just…
wanted to say goodbye.

137
00:05:13,444 --> 00:05:15,447
Say goodbye, like we're friends?

138
00:05:15,531 --> 00:05:17,407
-Yes.
-Oh, my God.

139
00:05:17,491 --> 00:05:19,367
How many times do I have to say this?

140
00:05:19,451 --> 00:05:22,370
We are coworkers, not friends.
Want some proof?

141
00:05:22,454 --> 00:05:24,748
Look, no friendship ring. Case closed.

142
00:05:24,832 --> 00:05:26,626
-Okay, okay.
-And I would like you

143
00:05:26,710 --> 00:05:28,044
to start treating me more professionally.

144
00:05:28,128 --> 00:05:29,754
Like keeping me in the loop.

145
00:05:29,838 --> 00:05:32,340
I mean, two months away
is gonna kill our momentum.

146
00:05:32,424 --> 00:05:33,883
A heads-up would've been nice.

147
00:05:33,967 --> 00:05:36,053
I'm sorry.
I thought I gave you a heads-up.

148
00:05:36,137 --> 00:05:38,337
-Yeah, yeah.
-WAITRESS: There you go, ladies.

149
00:05:40,641 --> 00:05:42,267
-What is that?
-Nothing.

150
00:05:42,351 --> 00:05:44,312
Miriam.

151
00:05:50,611 --> 00:05:52,153
What is it?

152
00:05:52,237 --> 00:05:54,740
It's a ring.

153
00:05:54,824 --> 00:05:56,492
-Holy fuck.
-But it is not a friendship ring.

154
00:05:56,576 --> 00:05:57,868
Eat your sandwich.

155
00:05:57,952 --> 00:05:59,161
It's just a ring I saw at the store.

156
00:05:59,245 --> 00:06:00,579
It was on sale.
I thought you would like it.

157
00:06:00,663 --> 00:06:02,164
-Two months.
-Plus, I get a 20% discount.

158
00:06:02,248 --> 00:06:05,252
-It's not that big a deal.
-Eat, eat.

159
00:06:12,134 --> 00:06:14,554
-Is it gold or silver?
-What?

160
00:06:14,638 --> 00:06:17,014
The ring, is it gold or silver?

161
00:06:17,098 --> 00:06:20,935
Silver.
You don't seem like a gold person.

162
00:06:21,019 --> 00:06:23,522
I'll take a look at it.

163
00:06:27,193 --> 00:06:28,735
Later.

164
00:06:28,819 --> 00:06:30,904
I can take it back.

165
00:06:30,988 --> 00:06:33,242
Two months.

166
00:06:35,619 --> 00:06:37,328
♪♪

167
00:06:37,412 --> 00:06:40,165
Everything's gonna fit!
My miniatures were spot on.

168
00:06:40,249 --> 00:06:42,458
-I still got it!
-ROSE: Good for you, Abe!

169
00:06:42,542 --> 00:06:44,378
Let's go. We want to beat the traffic.

170
00:06:44,462 --> 00:06:46,005
Such a beautiful day for a drive.

171
00:06:46,089 --> 00:06:47,339
MIDGE: Where's the baby?

172
00:06:47,423 --> 00:06:48,841
ROSE: I've got the baby, Miriam.

173
00:06:48,925 --> 00:06:51,594
-Hurry, Mommy!
-Don't run, Ethan.

174
00:06:51,678 --> 00:06:53,805
Goodbye, Zelda. We'll miss you.

175
00:06:53,889 --> 00:06:55,724
I'll miss you, too, Miss Miriam.

176
00:06:55,808 --> 00:06:58,268
We're going to the Catskills!

177
00:06:58,352 --> 00:07:01,730
<i>♪ Let's take a trip in a trailer ♪</i>

178
00:07:01,814 --> 00:07:04,567
<i>♪ No need to come back at all ♪</i>

179
00:07:04,651 --> 00:07:07,278
<i>♪ Oh, let's take a powder ♪</i>

180
00:07:07,362 --> 00:07:08,946
<i>♪ To Boston for chowder ♪</i>

181
00:07:09,030 --> 00:07:10,781
<i>♪ Let's get away from it all ♪</i>

182
00:07:10,865 --> 00:07:12,784
[LAUGHTER]

183
00:07:12,868 --> 00:07:16,246
<i>-♪ Let's go again to Niagara ♪
-♪ Do-do-do ♪</i>

184
00:07:16,330 --> 00:07:18,665
<i>♪ This time we'll look at the falls ♪</i>

185
00:07:18,749 --> 00:07:23,087
<i>-♪ Do-do-do-do-do ♪
-♪ Oh, let's get away ♪</i>

186
00:07:23,171 --> 00:07:26,549
<i>♪ From it all… ♪</i>

187
00:07:26,633 --> 00:07:29,552
-[PAULY CHUCKLING]
-♪ Let's get away from it all. ♪

188
00:07:29,636 --> 00:07:31,347
-Mr. Weissman!
-[CAR DOORS CLOSING]

189
00:07:31,431 --> 00:07:32,806
Oh, you look thin.

190
00:07:32,890 --> 00:07:34,391
Hello, Pauly. How have you been?

191
00:07:34,475 --> 00:07:36,060
Can't complain. Ladies!

192
00:07:36,144 --> 00:07:38,479
-Welcome back to Steiner Mountain Resort.
-[ABE SIGHS]

193
00:07:38,563 --> 00:07:40,064
-Your home away from home.
-Hi, Pauly.

194
00:07:40,148 --> 00:07:41,775
-Oh, good to see you, Pauly.
-[ABE CHUCKLES]

195
00:07:41,859 --> 00:07:43,902
It's your 27th year in a row, I believe.

196
00:07:43,986 --> 00:07:45,904
Your stats are correct, dear sir.

197
00:07:45,988 --> 00:07:48,406
Oh, smell that mountain air.
Invigorating.

198
00:07:48,490 --> 00:07:50,283
There's plenty more where that came from.

199
00:07:50,367 --> 00:07:52,536
Oh, here's Kent.
He'll be your kid camp coordinator.

200
00:07:52,620 --> 00:07:53,955
His name's actually David,

201
00:07:54,039 --> 00:07:55,498
but we wanted to keep the K-sound thing.

202
00:07:55,582 --> 00:07:56,540
-Uh-huh.
-Hi, everybody.

203
00:07:56,624 --> 00:07:58,251
-Hi, Kent.
-Hi, Ethan.

204
00:07:58,335 --> 00:08:00,044
It's potty and playtime. You ready to go?

205
00:08:00,128 --> 00:08:01,380
-Yeah!
-[LAUGHTER]

206
00:08:01,464 --> 00:08:03,006
We'll take him from here. Let's go!

207
00:08:03,090 --> 00:08:04,508
-Come on inside, gang.
-Bye, Mommy!

208
00:08:04,592 --> 00:08:05,759
-Let's get you all settled in.
-All right.

209
00:08:05,843 --> 00:08:07,177
KENT: Run, everybody, run!

210
00:08:07,261 --> 00:08:10,556
[KIDS SCREAMING PLAYFULLY]

211
00:08:10,640 --> 00:08:11,933
-[LIVELY CHATTER]
-[PHONES RINGING]

212
00:08:12,017 --> 00:08:13,726
I'm assuming you worked
up a thirst on your journey,

213
00:08:13,810 --> 00:08:15,353
-Mr. Weissman?
-That I did.

214
00:08:15,437 --> 00:08:17,063
Our signature Steiner tomato juice.

215
00:08:17,147 --> 00:08:19,190
Homemade and frosted to perfection.

216
00:08:19,274 --> 00:08:20,776
I've been hankering for it since August.

217
00:08:20,860 --> 00:08:22,611
-Ah.
-Mm.

218
00:08:22,695 --> 00:08:25,197
[SIGHS] It's the very taste of vacation.

219
00:08:25,281 --> 00:08:26,824
-Ah.
-Mr. Weissman.

220
00:08:26,908 --> 00:08:28,909
We have you in your
usual cottage by the lake.

221
00:08:28,993 --> 00:08:31,162
If I could just get you to
sign a couple of forms for me.

222
00:08:31,246 --> 00:08:32,914
Ooh, with blood or a pen?

223
00:08:32,998 --> 00:08:34,791
[LAUGHTER]

224
00:08:34,875 --> 00:08:37,711
Mr. Weissman, you should be on the stage.

225
00:08:37,795 --> 00:08:39,839
-A pen will do.
-Ah.

226
00:08:39,923 --> 00:08:41,048
And keep the pen.

227
00:08:41,132 --> 00:08:42,341
MIDGE: Three-legged race.

228
00:08:42,425 --> 00:08:44,802
-You're on.
-Goodbye, ladies.

229
00:08:44,886 --> 00:08:47,471
-Hello, Midge.
-Gabi. Good to see you.

230
00:08:47,555 --> 00:08:49,558
-How are the kids?
-Happy and healthy.

231
00:08:49,642 --> 00:08:51,643
And how far along in the process are you?

232
00:08:51,727 --> 00:08:52,936
-The process?
-With him.

233
00:08:53,020 --> 00:08:55,063
-Joel?
-[GROWLS]

234
00:08:55,147 --> 00:08:58,609
Oh, well, it's all kind of new,
and we're still figuring it out.

235
00:08:58,693 --> 00:09:00,320
He'll actually be up here later today.

236
00:09:00,404 --> 00:09:02,739
-Really?
-Yeah.

237
00:09:02,823 --> 00:09:03,865
Why?

238
00:09:03,949 --> 00:09:08,370
Well, the kids are
his, and he likes them,

239
00:09:08,454 --> 00:09:10,622
so he'll be coming back
and forth from the city.

240
00:09:10,706 --> 00:09:12,499
How modern.

241
00:09:12,583 --> 00:09:14,835
So I'll see you two ladies at the salon?

242
00:09:14,919 --> 00:09:16,045
-Yes, you will.
-Mm-hmm.

243
00:09:16,129 --> 00:09:18,923
Goodbye, Gabi.

244
00:09:19,007 --> 00:09:21,676
Oh, God. Is this what it's gonna be?

245
00:09:21,760 --> 00:09:23,970
[GROANS]: Grr.

246
00:09:24,054 --> 00:09:25,722
-There you go.
-PAULY: Okay.

247
00:09:25,806 --> 00:09:27,600
Now that you're all signed
in, let me introduce you

248
00:09:27,684 --> 00:09:29,310
to your boy for the summer, Mr. Weissman.

249
00:09:29,394 --> 00:09:31,854
Oh, well, no introduction necessary.

250
00:09:31,938 --> 00:09:34,648
-I raised Jimmy from a pup.
-Oh, it's not Jimmy.

251
00:09:34,732 --> 00:09:37,527
This is Samuel.
He's one of my best young boys.

252
00:09:37,611 --> 00:09:38,862
What happened to Jimmy?

253
00:09:38,946 --> 00:09:40,614
Good news. There were some stumbles,

254
00:09:40,698 --> 00:09:42,783
but he was finally accepted
to the internship he wanted.

255
00:09:42,867 --> 00:09:45,994
-Isn't that great?
-But I…

256
00:09:46,078 --> 00:09:47,663
Good for Jimmy.

257
00:09:47,747 --> 00:09:51,084
I'm at your service, Mr. Weissman.

258
00:09:51,168 --> 00:09:53,211
Your hand is wet.

259
00:09:53,295 --> 00:09:54,629
MALE ANNOUNCER
[OVER PA]: <i>Attention, guests.</i>

260
00:09:54,713 --> 00:09:56,339
<i>Just a reminder that
orientation in the main hall</i>

261
00:09:56,423 --> 00:09:57,800
<i>is one hour away. See you there.</i>

262
00:09:57,884 --> 00:09:59,259
You know the way, friends.

263
00:09:59,343 --> 00:10:00,844
Bring everything in the trailer,

264
00:10:00,928 --> 00:10:02,763
and there's a couple
of things in the trunk.

265
00:10:02,847 --> 00:10:05,641
There's a baby in the
backseat, Mr. Weissman.

266
00:10:05,725 --> 00:10:07,102
Bring that, too!

267
00:10:07,186 --> 00:10:08,937
SAMUEL: Right.

268
00:10:09,021 --> 00:10:11,773
ABE: Ah, that beautiful lake!

269
00:10:11,857 --> 00:10:13,859
[DOOR CREAKS]

270
00:10:15,861 --> 00:10:17,738
-Good morning.
-Ah, gentlemen.

271
00:10:17,822 --> 00:10:19,740
-I'll take this one.
-I'm right here, Mr. Weissman.

272
00:10:19,824 --> 00:10:21,283
MIDGE: Whew!
It needs to air out a little.

273
00:10:21,367 --> 00:10:22,660
ABE: Come on, guys. Hustle, hustle.

274
00:10:22,744 --> 00:10:24,412
ROSE: All the furniture's
in the wrong place.

275
00:10:24,496 --> 00:10:25,789
-MIDGE: We'll move it around.
-ABE: I left a diagram

276
00:10:25,873 --> 00:10:27,416
-for them last time.
-Well, they know how we like it.

277
00:10:27,500 --> 00:10:28,834
-It should've been ready.
-MIDGE: Those go to

278
00:10:28,918 --> 00:10:30,085
the second bedroom! The one on the left.

279
00:10:30,169 --> 00:10:31,378
ABE: The screen door needs adjusting.

280
00:10:31,462 --> 00:10:33,130
SAMUEL: I can do that for you, sir.

281
00:10:33,214 --> 00:10:34,840
ABE: Or someone from the proper
department can fix this, Jimmy.

282
00:10:34,924 --> 00:10:36,843
-It needs to be done right.
-MIDGE: Sorry, I meant right, not left.

283
00:10:36,927 --> 00:10:38,010
-Right. Right.
-SAMUEL: Right. Right.

284
00:10:38,094 --> 00:10:40,096
ROSE: Abe, make sure the
windows are open upstairs.

285
00:10:40,180 --> 00:10:41,639
-ABE: Right, got it.
-MIDGE: There's no room for this.

286
00:10:41,723 --> 00:10:43,307
ROSE: Just wedge it in, then
move that piece over here.

287
00:10:43,391 --> 00:10:44,642
No, no, don't put it on the couch.

288
00:10:44,726 --> 00:10:46,103
ABE: There's new carpeting on the stairs.

289
00:10:46,187 --> 00:10:47,771
MIDGE: Put it back, guys.
We've got to figure this out.

290
00:10:47,855 --> 00:10:48,897
ROSE: I've already figured this out.

291
00:10:48,981 --> 00:10:50,441
MIDGE: You just put
the couch on the chair.

292
00:10:50,525 --> 00:10:51,739
ROSE: This is more
luggage than last year.

293
00:10:51,823 --> 00:10:52,276
It's way more.

294
00:10:52,360 --> 00:10:53,360
ABE: Oh, beautiful day.

295
00:10:53,444 --> 00:10:54,821
ROSE: The luggage is
piling up in the kitchen.

296
00:10:54,905 --> 00:10:56,906
MIDGE: Oh, watch the lamp!
Watch the lamp!

297
00:10:56,990 --> 00:10:58,950
-Was this tree here last year?
-SAMUEL: Which tree?

298
00:10:59,034 --> 00:11:00,952
-I think it was there, Papa.
-ABE: I don't remember

299
00:11:01,036 --> 00:11:02,954
-this big tree being there.
-ROSE: Oh, there's an extra chair in here.

300
00:11:03,038 --> 00:11:04,582
SAMUEL: Can I help you
with the tree, Mr. Weissman?

301
00:11:04,666 --> 00:11:06,667
ABE: How could you
possibly help me with the tree?

302
00:11:06,751 --> 00:11:08,169
Explain yourself.

303
00:11:08,253 --> 00:11:10,171
MIDGE: Ah, I forgot Esther's doll.

304
00:11:10,255 --> 00:11:11,881
-ROSE: Which one?
-Betsy Wetsy. I knew I forgot something.

305
00:11:11,965 --> 00:11:13,591
ROSE: We'll have Jimmy
run out for a new doll.

306
00:11:13,675 --> 00:11:15,135
MIDGE: That'll wet itself?
It has to wet itself.

307
00:11:15,219 --> 00:11:17,012
ABE: What's the couch doing outside?

308
00:11:17,096 --> 00:11:19,014
-ROSE: It's just temporary!
-ELIANA: Oh, Midge.

309
00:11:19,098 --> 00:11:21,683
-ABE: It'll get dirty out here.
-Oh, sorry about Joel, Midge.

310
00:11:21,767 --> 00:11:22,511
MIDGE: It's okay, Eliana.

311
00:11:22,595 --> 00:11:24,061
-Are you devastated?
-Fresh tomato juice, sir?

312
00:11:24,145 --> 00:11:26,355
You were getting luggage; now
you're bringing me tomato juice?

313
00:11:26,439 --> 00:11:28,691
ELIANA: Oh, good, good, you
should move on. Such a cad.

314
00:11:28,775 --> 00:11:30,359
MIDGE: There's one too
many cooks in the kitchen.

315
00:11:30,443 --> 00:11:31,944
ROSE: There's a cook in the kitchen?

316
00:11:32,028 --> 00:11:33,012
-Watch out!
-ABE: Oh!

317
00:11:33,096 --> 00:11:33,864
[GLASS BREAKS]

318
00:11:33,948 --> 00:11:36,617
-ABE: Jimmy!
-ROSE: There's tomato juice everywhere!

319
00:11:36,701 --> 00:11:38,452
-SAMUEL: I'll get a mop!
-Oh, Abe.

320
00:11:38,536 --> 00:11:40,454
-MIDGE: Where's the towel?
-We need some help here.

321
00:11:40,538 --> 00:11:44,459
ABE: And he forgot the baby.
Jimmy, bring a mop and the baby.

322
00:11:44,543 --> 00:11:47,212
-MIDGE: Why is the couch outside?
-ROSE: I don't know.

323
00:11:47,296 --> 00:11:48,463
I think the layout in there works.

324
00:11:48,547 --> 00:11:50,173
I think it works, too.

325
00:11:50,257 --> 00:11:52,342
And I think it's exactly the
way it was when we got here.

326
00:11:52,426 --> 00:11:54,345
-But I think we've proven that it's right.
-Mm.

327
00:11:54,429 --> 00:11:56,805
-All situated, ladies?
-Yes, Pauly, thank you.

328
00:11:56,889 --> 00:11:58,682
Abe's upstairs. I'll get him for you.

329
00:11:58,766 --> 00:12:00,100
Abe!

330
00:12:00,184 --> 00:12:02,394
Actually, I'm here to talk to Miriam.

331
00:12:02,478 --> 00:12:04,147
-Mind if I sit?
-No. Pauly, please.

332
00:12:04,231 --> 00:12:06,233
MALE ANNOUNCER [OVER PA]: <i>Carl Finger.
Paging Carl Finger.</i>

333
00:12:06,317 --> 00:12:09,611
<i>Not an emergency, but not
not an emergency, either.</i>

334
00:12:09,695 --> 00:12:11,696
Now, orientation is in a few minutes,

335
00:12:11,780 --> 00:12:14,575
-so I don't want to keep you long.
-Sure. What's up?

336
00:12:14,659 --> 00:12:17,286
[CLEARS THROAT] It's about
the swimsuit competition.

337
00:12:17,370 --> 00:12:19,330
-Mm, the Mrs. Steiner Pageant?
-What about it?

338
00:12:19,414 --> 00:12:20,915
We're all aware of your record, Miriam.

339
00:12:20,999 --> 00:12:24,127
What a feat: eight wins in a
row in three different categories.

340
00:12:24,211 --> 00:12:26,338
And you get lovelier every
year, just like your mother.

341
00:12:26,422 --> 00:12:28,090
-Oh.
-But this year, I think we have

342
00:12:28,174 --> 00:12:30,175
a new and exciting proposition for you.

343
00:12:30,259 --> 00:12:32,887
-Fun. What is it?
-Sash girl.

344
00:12:32,971 --> 00:12:34,430
Sash girl?

345
00:12:34,514 --> 00:12:36,057
But the sash girl doesn't compete.

346
00:12:36,141 --> 00:12:37,809
She just hands the sash to the winner.

347
00:12:37,893 --> 00:12:39,852
-That's right.
-But what if I win?

348
00:12:39,936 --> 00:12:41,229
I hand the sash to myself?

349
00:12:41,313 --> 00:12:42,606
The photograph will look ridiculous.

350
00:12:42,690 --> 00:12:44,608
Look, you've competed as a teen,

351
00:12:44,692 --> 00:12:46,902
as an ingénue, and in
the Mrs. Steiner Pageant

352
00:12:46,986 --> 00:12:49,530
these past four years, but
this year, we're hard-pressed

353
00:12:49,614 --> 00:12:52,617
to make the argument that
you are any of those things.

354
00:12:52,701 --> 00:12:55,328
Not after the recent
change in your situation.

355
00:12:55,412 --> 00:12:56,913
But I'm technically still married.

356
00:12:56,997 --> 00:12:59,124
Yes, but the Mrs. Steiner
Swimsuit Pageant winner

357
00:12:59,208 --> 00:13:00,835
is always accompanied by her husband.

358
00:13:00,919 --> 00:13:04,463
And having him there with you…
might cast a pall.

359
00:13:04,547 --> 00:13:06,966
-I see.
-But of course we want you there,

360
00:13:07,050 --> 00:13:08,926
and that's why we'd like
you to enjoy the honor

361
00:13:09,010 --> 00:13:10,554
of handing the sash
to this year's winner.

362
00:13:10,638 --> 00:13:11,805
But what about the weird old lady

363
00:13:11,889 --> 00:13:13,056
who always hands out the sash?

364
00:13:13,140 --> 00:13:14,725
That would be my grandmother.

365
00:13:14,809 --> 00:13:16,852
Sorry. Won't she be disappointed?

366
00:13:16,936 --> 00:13:19,313
-She passed.
-So I guess she won't mind.

367
00:13:19,397 --> 00:13:21,899
I appreciate your understanding.

368
00:13:21,983 --> 00:13:24,569
And on the bright side,

369
00:13:24,653 --> 00:13:27,071
you're free to load up
on rice pudding tonight.

370
00:13:27,155 --> 00:13:30,200
[CHUCKLES] See you at orientation.

371
00:13:30,284 --> 00:13:32,286
Hershey?

372
00:13:32,370 --> 00:13:34,622
I just got kicked out of
the swimsuit pageant.

373
00:13:34,706 --> 00:13:36,373
That does it.

374
00:13:36,457 --> 00:13:40,378
You're definitely wearing
the Mamie Van Doren.

375
00:13:40,462 --> 00:13:42,505
ANNOUNCER [OVER PA]:
<i>Paging Leon Zigglestein.</i>

376
00:13:42,589 --> 00:13:44,758
<i>Please come get your
wallet at the front desk.</i>

377
00:13:44,842 --> 00:13:46,426
<i>Mr. Leon Zigglestein.</i>

378
00:13:46,510 --> 00:13:49,262
-[LIVELY CHATTER]
-Ah.

379
00:13:49,346 --> 00:13:51,265
PAULY: Let's all grab seats, everybody.

380
00:13:51,349 --> 00:13:53,809
We'll begin here in a minute.

381
00:13:53,893 --> 00:13:55,895
Miriam Maisel.

382
00:13:55,979 --> 00:13:57,730
Alya Feinburg, good to see you.

383
00:13:57,814 --> 00:13:59,358
-You, too.
-And how's Marv?

384
00:13:59,442 --> 00:14:01,151
Uh, I can't get him off the links.

385
00:14:01,235 --> 00:14:02,986
A widow to golf, and yet so young.

386
00:14:03,070 --> 00:14:06,073
I thought we should touch
base about this thing with Joel.

387
00:14:06,157 --> 00:14:08,367
-All right.
-The four of us have spent

388
00:14:08,451 --> 00:14:10,912
so much time together
up here, playing charades,

389
00:14:10,996 --> 00:14:13,915
the bowling team,
all the stuff friends do.

390
00:14:13,999 --> 00:14:15,792
-Yes?
-Well, Marv and I

391
00:14:15,876 --> 00:14:17,043
[WHISPERS]: discussed it,

392
00:14:17,127 --> 00:14:19,046
and we were pretty much in agreement that

393
00:14:19,130 --> 00:14:21,465
he's actually a better friend
of Joel's than I am of yours.

394
00:14:21,549 --> 00:14:22,966
-Okay. I get it.
-So…

395
00:14:23,050 --> 00:14:24,760
We'll still run into each other.

396
00:14:24,844 --> 00:14:26,220
Buffet line, bathroom.

397
00:14:26,304 --> 00:14:27,846
-I'm glad you understand.
-Mm-hmm.

398
00:14:27,930 --> 00:14:29,766
So are you changing your name?

399
00:14:29,850 --> 00:14:31,518
-To Zippy Maisel.
-Really?

400
00:14:31,602 --> 00:14:33,144
-No.
-You're fun.

401
00:14:33,228 --> 00:14:36,315
-Just not as fun as Joel.
-Bye.

402
00:14:37,566 --> 00:14:39,985
PAULY: All right, here we go.

403
00:14:40,069 --> 00:14:42,738
-Good afternoon, my beauties!
-CROWD: Hi, Pauly!

404
00:14:42,822 --> 00:14:45,157
Now, most of you know
me, but for those who don't,

405
00:14:45,241 --> 00:14:49,538
I'm Pauly Auerbach, just
beginning my 18th fabulous year

406
00:14:49,622 --> 00:14:52,165
as your Steiner executive director.

407
00:14:52,249 --> 00:14:54,126
And, oh, boy, I'm gonna
have a heart attack

408
00:14:54,210 --> 00:14:55,711
from all the exciting activities

409
00:14:55,795 --> 00:14:57,839
we got planned for you this season!

410
00:14:57,923 --> 00:15:00,258
[CROWD CHEERING]

411
00:15:00,342 --> 00:15:02,635
Now, each of you

412
00:15:02,719 --> 00:15:05,513
will find a Steiner
newsletter under your seat,

413
00:15:05,597 --> 00:15:08,100
Issue Number One for 1959.

414
00:15:08,184 --> 00:15:10,561
And if you think you
notice a fun new font,

415
00:15:10,645 --> 00:15:13,188
you're not wrong. Good eye.

416
00:15:13,272 --> 00:15:15,816
Oh, finally!
I hated the old font, hated it.

417
00:15:15,900 --> 00:15:17,819
PAULY: In it is a map of the property,

418
00:15:17,903 --> 00:15:20,029
some things you need
to know, and of course

419
00:15:20,113 --> 00:15:22,741
a list of upcoming
activities for the week.

420
00:15:22,825 --> 00:15:24,659
And here's hoping
that our returning guests

421
00:15:24,743 --> 00:15:26,996
will take all you
newcomers under their wing

422
00:15:27,080 --> 00:15:28,956
to give them the lay of the land,

423
00:15:29,040 --> 00:15:31,584
and to show them what's
mud and what's bear bleep.

424
00:15:31,668 --> 00:15:33,502
[LAUGHTER]

425
00:15:33,586 --> 00:15:35,171
Now, there is a young man here

426
00:15:35,255 --> 00:15:37,174
that a lot of you already know and love,

427
00:15:37,258 --> 00:15:38,925
our entertainment
director, Buzz Goldberg.

428
00:15:39,009 --> 00:15:41,511
Come on up and take the mic, Buzz.

429
00:15:41,595 --> 00:15:45,056
Hello, Steinerites!
How's everybody doing?

430
00:15:45,140 --> 00:15:48,227
[CROWD CHEERING]

431
00:15:48,311 --> 00:15:51,439
You all may not have met
me, but you know what I do:

432
00:15:51,523 --> 00:15:53,232
-I manufacture fun.
-[CROWD MURMURS EXCITEDLY]

433
00:15:53,316 --> 00:15:55,318
And it seems like I could
whip up a little right now.

434
00:15:55,402 --> 00:15:57,529
-What do you say?
-[CHEERING]

435
00:15:57,613 --> 00:16:00,324
Hey, now, what are all these
employees doing standing around?

436
00:16:00,408 --> 00:16:02,993
Get on up here and help me lead the group

437
00:16:03,077 --> 00:16:05,205
in the "Steiner Resort Welcome Song."

438
00:16:05,289 --> 00:16:06,956
[CROWD WHOOPING]

439
00:16:07,040 --> 00:16:08,750
[PLAYS NOTE]

440
00:16:08,834 --> 00:16:10,627
One, two, three, four.

441
00:16:10,711 --> 00:16:12,837
[TO "CAROLINA IN THE MORNING"]
<i>♪ Nothing could be finer ♪</i>

442
00:16:12,921 --> 00:16:16,759
<i>♪ Than to spend the day
at Steiner in the summer ♪</i>

443
00:16:16,843 --> 00:16:18,677
Ah, you remember it!

444
00:16:18,761 --> 00:16:21,430
<i>♪ Nothing much convinces
like the taste of Steiner blintzes ♪</i>

445
00:16:21,514 --> 00:16:23,974
<i>♪ In the summer ♪</i>

446
00:16:24,058 --> 00:16:25,977
Just the girls now.

447
00:16:26,061 --> 00:16:29,397
<i>♪ Play all day and dance all night ♪</i>

448
00:16:29,481 --> 00:16:33,902
-Now the boys.
<i>-♪ All us happy Israelites… ♪</i>

449
00:16:33,986 --> 00:16:35,905
[JOSH CONTINUES HOLDING NOTE]

450
00:16:35,989 --> 00:16:38,449
Oh, boy.
Looks like we have a note challenge.

451
00:16:38,533 --> 00:16:40,952
-CROWD: Note challenge!
-The resort record

452
00:16:41,036 --> 00:16:43,120
for holding that last note is 42 seconds.

453
00:16:43,204 --> 00:16:44,623
Let's see how he does, folks.

454
00:16:44,707 --> 00:16:46,542
[CONTINUES HOLDING NOTE]

455
00:16:46,626 --> 00:16:49,795
I hit some traffic.
Did I miss the bear shit joke?

456
00:16:49,879 --> 00:16:51,964
-Yes, you did.
-Ah, hell.

457
00:16:52,048 --> 00:16:53,800
This guy's an amateur.

458
00:16:53,884 --> 00:16:55,009
<i>-♪ …ites. ♪</i>
-[CROWD CHEERS]

459
00:16:55,093 --> 00:16:56,803
Ah, not a record,
but a heck of an effort.

460
00:16:56,887 --> 00:16:58,304
-Good try, Josh.
-[APPLAUSE]

461
00:16:58,388 --> 00:17:00,390
-[CHUCKLES]
-[PLAYS NOTE]

462
00:17:00,474 --> 00:17:02,392
<i>♪ So skip the luxury liner ♪</i>

463
00:17:02,476 --> 00:17:08,190
<i>♪ To enjoy a schvitz at
Steiner in the summer ♪</i>

464
00:17:08,274 --> 00:17:10,150
ALL [CHANTING]: Steiner! Steiner!

465
00:17:10,234 --> 00:17:12,152
-Steiner!
-[FEET STOMPING RHYTHMICALLY]

466
00:17:12,236 --> 00:17:15,657
We're finer! Finer! Finer!

467
00:17:15,741 --> 00:17:18,076
-How's it going here since you arrived?
-Steiner. Steiner.

468
00:17:18,160 --> 00:17:20,579
-Fine, I guess.
-[CROWD CONTINUES CHANTING]

469
00:17:20,663 --> 00:17:23,374
-Anybody mention anything about…
-Us? Oh, yeah.

470
00:17:23,458 --> 00:17:25,209
Me, too.

471
00:17:25,293 --> 00:17:27,753
I was here ten minutes, and I
got corralled by three people.

472
00:17:27,837 --> 00:17:29,130
I've gotten it all day.

473
00:17:29,214 --> 00:17:30,756
They even kicked me
out of the swimsuit pageant

474
00:17:30,840 --> 00:17:32,593
'cause I'm no longer a missus.

475
00:17:32,677 --> 00:17:35,387
-What?
-I get to be sash girl.

476
00:17:35,471 --> 00:17:38,140
But sash girl just hands out the sash.

477
00:17:38,224 --> 00:17:40,183
Pauly has spoken.

478
00:17:40,267 --> 00:17:41,602
Steiner!

479
00:17:41,686 --> 00:17:43,605
Good job! Applaud yourselves, everyone!

480
00:17:43,689 --> 00:17:46,274
[CROWD CHEERING]

481
00:17:46,358 --> 00:17:48,359
Anything I can get for you, Mr. Weissman?

482
00:17:48,443 --> 00:17:49,986
PAULY: Thank you, Buzz. Great job.

483
00:17:50,070 --> 00:17:52,156
You'll never be Jimmy.

484
00:17:52,240 --> 00:17:54,617
PAULY: Now, friends, last
year there was some kvetching

485
00:17:54,701 --> 00:17:57,453
that the resort was short on
certain recreation equipment.

486
00:17:57,537 --> 00:17:59,914
Well, listen to me and
listen to me carefully.

487
00:17:59,998 --> 00:18:03,919
This year, there will be more hula hoops.

488
00:18:04,003 --> 00:18:06,087
-WOMAN: Yeah!
-There will be

489
00:18:06,171 --> 00:18:08,798
-more floaties.
-[WHOOPING, CLAPPING]

490
00:18:08,882 --> 00:18:11,260
And there will be more balls!

491
00:18:11,344 --> 00:18:14,221
[CROWD CHEERING]

492
00:18:14,305 --> 00:18:16,390
JOEL: Nothing to see here, Asher!

493
00:18:16,474 --> 00:18:18,267
PAULY: On a happier note,

494
00:18:18,351 --> 00:18:20,269
let's wish all our
newlyweds mazel tov, yes?

495
00:18:20,353 --> 00:18:22,814
Some of whom met right
here at Steiner Mountain Resort

496
00:18:22,898 --> 00:18:25,651
and made a blessed, lifelong commitment.

497
00:18:25,735 --> 00:18:27,110
Are you kidding me?

498
00:18:27,194 --> 00:18:28,904
There's Izzy and Enid Schulburg.

499
00:18:30,322 --> 00:18:32,116
Neil and Phyllis Cohen.

500
00:18:32,200 --> 00:18:35,578
And Allie and Taavi Applebaum,
who met playing shuffleboard.

501
00:18:35,662 --> 00:18:39,707
To all our happy couples,
may you have life, luck,

502
00:18:39,791 --> 00:18:41,835
and lots of little Steinerites!

503
00:18:41,919 --> 00:18:43,629
[APPLAUSE]

504
00:18:43,713 --> 00:18:44,797
What are you doing?

505
00:18:44,881 --> 00:18:46,715
Hey, Steiner guests,
can I get your attention?

506
00:18:46,799 --> 00:18:48,550
Sorry, Pauly. This'll just take a second.

507
00:18:48,634 --> 00:18:51,846
Most of you know me. Joel Maisel.

508
00:18:51,930 --> 00:18:55,600
And an awful lot of you are staring at me.
And Midge.

509
00:18:55,684 --> 00:18:57,352
Now, you know what happened to us.

510
00:18:57,436 --> 00:18:59,897
We're separated, okay?
But we're still close.

511
00:18:59,981 --> 00:19:01,857
Our families are close.

512
00:19:01,941 --> 00:19:03,776
And we love our kids,
and they both love us,

513
00:19:03,860 --> 00:19:05,277
so everything's fine.

514
00:19:05,361 --> 00:19:08,030
Really, there's nothing to stare at here.

515
00:19:08,114 --> 00:19:10,283
You can still be friends with me, or not.

516
00:19:10,367 --> 00:19:12,536
And you can still be
friends with Midge, or not.

517
00:19:12,620 --> 00:19:13,996
It's up to you.

518
00:19:14,080 --> 00:19:16,164
And, Pauly, shame on
you for not letting Midge

519
00:19:16,248 --> 00:19:18,333
in the Mrs. Steiner Swimsuit Pageant.

520
00:19:18,417 --> 00:19:20,211
She's eight years a
champion and a huge draw,

521
00:19:20,295 --> 00:19:21,754
and every $25 award she won,

522
00:19:21,838 --> 00:19:23,673
she donated to an
orphans home in the Bronx.

523
00:19:23,757 --> 00:19:26,843
So this year, thanks to you,
some orphans are going hungry.

524
00:19:26,927 --> 00:19:28,594
[CROWD MURMURS]

525
00:19:28,678 --> 00:19:30,431
So we're clear? Yes?

526
00:19:30,515 --> 00:19:32,182
-[MAN COUGHS]
-Good.

527
00:19:32,266 --> 00:19:35,728
So, have fun, everybody.
See you dockside.

528
00:19:37,814 --> 00:19:39,733
PAULY: Always expect the unexpected

529
00:19:39,817 --> 00:19:41,776
here at Steiner Mountain Resort.

530
00:19:41,860 --> 00:19:43,778
Well, you know what I always say.

531
00:19:43,862 --> 00:19:45,196
Abi gezunt!

532
00:19:45,280 --> 00:19:47,699
-Everybody! Abi?
-CROWD: Gezunt!

533
00:19:47,783 --> 00:19:49,867
PAULY: Well, that's all that's
on the docket, everybody.

534
00:19:49,951 --> 00:19:50,369
[APPLAUSE]

535
00:19:50,453 --> 00:19:52,830
So enjoy your summer, enjoy your stay,

536
00:19:52,914 --> 00:19:55,458
because before you
know it, it'll be over.

537
00:19:55,542 --> 00:19:58,129
I'll see you tonight.

538
00:19:59,630 --> 00:20:01,715
MALE ANNOUNCER:
<i>Steinerites, the pool is now open.</i>

539
00:20:01,799 --> 00:20:03,884
Remember, we have our
salon appointments later.

540
00:20:03,968 --> 00:20:05,469
-I will be there.
-Mm-hmm.

541
00:20:05,553 --> 00:20:07,137
-So what building are you in?
-Hmm?

542
00:20:07,221 --> 00:20:09,807
What building?
Are you north side, south side?

543
00:20:09,891 --> 00:20:11,934
-Oh, shit.
-What?

544
00:20:12,018 --> 00:20:14,187
-I don't have a room.
-You don't have a room?

545
00:20:14,271 --> 00:20:16,272
I'm always in the cottage
with you and your parents,

546
00:20:16,356 --> 00:20:18,317
so it didn't even occur
to me to book one.

547
00:20:18,401 --> 00:20:20,027
Still getting used to
some things, I guess.

548
00:20:20,111 --> 00:20:22,321
Well, go see if they
have something available.

549
00:20:22,405 --> 00:20:24,782
I heard people talking.
There's a gigantic waiting list.

550
00:20:24,866 --> 00:20:27,160
Such an idiot. Guess I'll go back.

551
00:20:27,244 --> 00:20:29,162
Don't go back. You just got here.

552
00:20:29,246 --> 00:20:31,164
I could throw myself
on the mercy of Pauly,

553
00:20:31,248 --> 00:20:33,166
but I don't think he's my
closest friend right now.

554
00:20:33,250 --> 00:20:35,960
Look, just stay on our sun
porch till you figure it out.

555
00:20:36,044 --> 00:20:37,630
Really?

556
00:20:37,714 --> 00:20:39,799
Ethan can sleep out there with you.
He'll love it.

557
00:20:39,883 --> 00:20:41,300
Will your parents love it?

558
00:20:41,384 --> 00:20:43,385
They'll be fine. I'll make it fine.

559
00:20:43,469 --> 00:20:45,471
Okay. Thanks.

560
00:20:48,392 --> 00:20:49,684
MALE ANNOUNCER
[OVER PA]: <i>Attention, guests.</i>

561
00:20:49,768 --> 00:20:51,311
<i>Tonight's vodka and latke mixer will be</i>

562
00:20:51,395 --> 00:20:53,146
<i>in the rec room at 8 p.m.</i>

563
00:20:53,230 --> 00:20:55,273
The ladies just headed out to the salon.

564
00:20:55,357 --> 00:20:58,611
Yeah, Rose told me that
was where they were heading.

565
00:20:58,695 --> 00:21:01,781
Abe… I promise I won't be in your way.

566
00:21:01,865 --> 00:21:03,741
I'll store my stuff under the staircase.

567
00:21:03,825 --> 00:21:05,994
You'll never see it.
You'll hardly know I'm here.

568
00:21:06,078 --> 00:21:07,329
It's fine, Joel.

569
00:21:07,413 --> 00:21:08,872
Sorry, with everything going on,

570
00:21:08,956 --> 00:21:10,499
booking a room just slipped my mind.

571
00:21:10,583 --> 00:21:12,167
Ah, it's fine, really.

572
00:21:12,251 --> 00:21:14,670
A room will open up soon enough.

573
00:21:18,383 --> 00:21:19,425
Anything else?

574
00:21:19,509 --> 00:21:22,804
Look, Joel, up here in the mountains,

575
00:21:22,888 --> 00:21:25,432
I do… different kinds of things.

576
00:21:25,516 --> 00:21:27,017
You drink a lot of tomato juice.

577
00:21:27,101 --> 00:21:30,146
Not just the tomato juice.
I have a morning routine.

578
00:21:30,230 --> 00:21:33,524
Every day, before the sun's
up, when everyone's asleep,

579
00:21:33,608 --> 00:21:36,862
I do my special outdoor calisthenics.

580
00:21:36,946 --> 00:21:38,363
I didn't know that.

581
00:21:38,447 --> 00:21:40,448
And I wear special clothing.

582
00:21:40,532 --> 00:21:42,033
And now that you're down here,

583
00:21:42,117 --> 00:21:44,369
you're bound to see me when I head out.

584
00:21:44,453 --> 00:21:46,205
-Special clothing?
-A romper, Joel.

585
00:21:46,289 --> 00:21:48,207
-I wear a romper.
-What's a romper?

586
00:21:48,291 --> 00:21:49,876
It's a one-piece exercise outfit.

587
00:21:49,960 --> 00:21:51,127
Oh.

588
00:21:51,211 --> 00:21:53,671
Very tight-fitting, and
no one has seen me in it,

589
00:21:53,755 --> 00:21:55,299
not even Rose.

590
00:21:55,383 --> 00:21:59,845
But now, you may see me in it.

591
00:21:59,929 --> 00:22:02,181
You should be prepared.

592
00:22:02,265 --> 00:22:04,685
Okay.

593
00:22:10,023 --> 00:22:11,774
Anything else?

594
00:22:11,858 --> 00:22:14,153
I'm wondering if I should
put it on and show it to you.

595
00:22:14,237 --> 00:22:16,488
-Oh, no, Abe, no.
-Just so we can get beyond it.

596
00:22:16,572 --> 00:22:18,157
I really don't think that's necessary.

597
00:22:18,241 --> 00:22:20,034
-You haven't seen it.
-I sleep very deeply.

598
00:22:20,118 --> 00:22:22,786
Really, don't even think about me.

599
00:22:22,870 --> 00:22:26,625
Okay. I'll try not to.

600
00:22:29,878 --> 00:22:32,130
[SLURPS LOUDLY]

601
00:22:32,214 --> 00:22:34,759
MALE ANNOUNCER [OVER PA]:
<i>Ladies, Chef Seymour Silver invites you</i>

602
00:22:34,843 --> 00:22:36,510
<i>to join him in the trailside lounge</i>

603
00:22:36,594 --> 00:22:38,512
<i>at 2:15 for a garniture demonstration.</i>

604
00:22:38,596 --> 00:22:40,556
<i>That's 2:15 in the trailside lounge.</i>

605
00:22:40,640 --> 00:22:43,393
You know, he hypnotized her
at the mesmerism show last year,

606
00:22:43,477 --> 00:22:45,479
and to this day, she
still clucks like a chicken

607
00:22:45,563 --> 00:22:47,105
-when you clap your hands.
-No.

608
00:22:47,189 --> 00:22:49,274
-[MIDGE LAUGHS]
-All that clucking at orientation,

609
00:22:49,358 --> 00:22:50,859
that was Lottie Friedman.

610
00:22:50,943 --> 00:22:52,946
I'll give her this, she
clucks on the beat.

611
00:22:53,030 --> 00:22:54,489
[LAUGHTER]

612
00:22:54,573 --> 00:22:56,407
Oh, you see Saul over there?

613
00:22:56,491 --> 00:22:58,743
-ROSE: Oh, dear.
-EDIE: You know, his wife died.

614
00:22:58,827 --> 00:23:00,119
Yes, a tragedy.

615
00:23:00,203 --> 00:23:01,704
Well, she's not dead three months

616
00:23:01,788 --> 00:23:03,582
when he turns around
and marries her kid sister.

617
00:23:03,666 --> 00:23:04,750
Joanie?

618
00:23:04,834 --> 00:23:06,543
But the man is still on
the prowl; look at him.

619
00:23:06,627 --> 00:23:08,545
At the "End of Summer" soirée last year,

620
00:23:08,629 --> 00:23:10,297
he danced with Leah Bernstein.

621
00:23:10,381 --> 00:23:12,300
And when he pressed up against her,

622
00:23:12,384 --> 00:23:14,302
she could feel his excitement.

623
00:23:14,386 --> 00:23:16,304
Oh, kind of wishing you hadn't said that.

624
00:23:16,388 --> 00:23:17,973
It may have been a pocketknife.

625
00:23:18,057 --> 00:23:20,642
[CHUCKLES]: Yes, a pocketknife!

626
00:23:20,726 --> 00:23:23,312
Well, I'll see you two tonight.

627
00:23:23,396 --> 00:23:25,731
My God, you look like sisters.

628
00:23:25,815 --> 00:23:29,026
-If only. See you tonight, Edie.
-Bye, Edie.

629
00:23:29,110 --> 00:23:32,281
Let's get you to the dryers, ladies.

630
00:23:32,365 --> 00:23:35,200
Mama, thanks for letting Joel
stay with us for a few nights.

631
00:23:35,284 --> 00:23:37,661
He got stuck, and I
want him to see the kids.

632
00:23:37,745 --> 00:23:39,538
Oh, it was fine.

633
00:23:39,622 --> 00:23:41,249
I'll get you some lemonade.

634
00:23:41,333 --> 00:23:43,668
It was very nice what
he did at the orientation.

635
00:23:43,752 --> 00:23:45,378
Surprisingly manly.

636
00:23:45,462 --> 00:23:47,213
Let's hope it stops all this silliness.

637
00:23:47,297 --> 00:23:48,464
From your lips.

638
00:23:48,548 --> 00:23:49,882
Relationships should be private.

639
00:23:49,966 --> 00:23:51,427
-Don't you think?
-Amen.

640
00:23:51,511 --> 00:23:53,095
So, are you dating?

641
00:23:53,179 --> 00:23:54,471
-What?
-Are you dating?

642
00:23:54,555 --> 00:23:56,181
What's your dating life? I know nothing.

643
00:23:56,265 --> 00:23:58,600
I guess my dating life
doesn't get to be private.

644
00:23:58,684 --> 00:24:01,438
You're just out late so
often, what else would it be?

645
00:24:01,522 --> 00:24:06,026
Well, as a matter of fact,
yes, I am dating a little bit.

646
00:24:06,110 --> 00:24:07,944
Anyone I know?
Anyone from the neighborhood?

647
00:24:08,028 --> 00:24:09,779
No, I'm kind of just getting around.

648
00:24:09,863 --> 00:24:11,615
I mean, not "getting around."

649
00:24:11,699 --> 00:24:13,868
It's just that I'm not being
geographically snobby.

650
00:24:13,952 --> 00:24:15,328
-You know?
-I guess.

651
00:24:15,412 --> 00:24:17,330
I'm kind of hitting all five boroughs.

652
00:24:17,414 --> 00:24:19,040
Well, that doesn't seem right.

653
00:24:19,124 --> 00:24:20,751
Don't your friends have
anyone to set you up with?

654
00:24:20,835 --> 00:24:22,586
-Nope.
-Not even that little blonde thing

655
00:24:22,670 --> 00:24:24,129
that talks all high and chirpy?

656
00:24:24,213 --> 00:24:27,049
Imogene.
Nope, all her friends are Gentiles.

657
00:24:27,133 --> 00:24:30,094
Oh. Well, tell me about these
Jewish men you're seeing,

658
00:24:30,178 --> 00:24:32,221
like that man that gave you the fur coat.

659
00:24:32,305 --> 00:24:34,349
-Fur coat?
-You wore it to synagogue last year.

660
00:24:34,433 --> 00:24:37,393
-What is he, a furrier?
-No, a trapper.

661
00:24:37,477 --> 00:24:39,313
But it was a short-lived thing.

662
00:24:39,397 --> 00:24:41,357
He was a little Paul Bunyan for my taste.

663
00:24:41,441 --> 00:24:43,275
-You dated a trapper?
-And a cab driver.

664
00:24:43,359 --> 00:24:44,735
-You didn't.
-And a carny.

665
00:24:44,819 --> 00:24:46,528
I actually met the carny, oddly enough,

666
00:24:46,612 --> 00:24:48,530
because the date with
the cab driver was so awful

667
00:24:48,614 --> 00:24:49,908
I told him to let me out of the car,

668
00:24:49,992 --> 00:24:51,326
and we were in Coney
Island, and I got out,

669
00:24:51,410 --> 00:24:52,535
and there was the carny.

670
00:24:52,619 --> 00:24:53,953
-My God.
-So he and I had a drink.

671
00:24:54,037 --> 00:24:55,163
And it was nice. And he introduced me

672
00:24:55,247 --> 00:24:56,915
to his sister, Koo Koo the Bird Girl,

673
00:24:56,999 --> 00:24:58,416
but I thought, "Where could this go?"

674
00:24:58,500 --> 00:25:00,336
Koo Koo was nice, but
I don't want to end up

675
00:25:00,420 --> 00:25:01,420
living in a circus tent.

676
00:25:01,504 --> 00:25:03,422
-Is this a joke?
-It's the truth.

677
00:25:03,506 --> 00:25:05,091
Are you intimate with any of these men?

678
00:25:05,175 --> 00:25:06,634
Oh, no, it hasn't gotten that far.

679
00:25:06,718 --> 00:25:08,177
-But, Miriam, when…
-Mm, sorry, Mama.

680
00:25:08,261 --> 00:25:10,097
If I don't start now,
my hair will never dry,

681
00:25:10,181 --> 00:25:11,723
and I'll be late picking
up Esther from the sitter.

682
00:25:11,807 --> 00:25:13,225
Pick it up, Goldie.

683
00:25:13,309 --> 00:25:15,227
I'm glad we talked, though.
It's been weighing on me.

684
00:25:15,311 --> 00:25:17,649
Okay, but I'm gonna keep
on the lookout for you. Okay?

685
00:25:17,733 --> 00:25:18,481
[DRYER WHIRRING]

686
00:25:18,565 --> 00:25:18,827
What?

687
00:25:18,911 --> 00:25:21,734
[LOUDER] I'm gonna be
on the lookout for a man.

688
00:25:21,818 --> 00:25:24,821
Fine.

689
00:25:24,905 --> 00:25:26,823
♪♪

690
00:25:26,907 --> 00:25:29,327
<i>♪ The way you hold your knife ♪</i>

691
00:25:30,912 --> 00:25:34,581
<i>♪ The way we danced till 3:00 ♪</i>

692
00:25:34,665 --> 00:25:38,711
<i>♪ The way you changed my life ♪</i>

693
00:25:38,795 --> 00:25:42,799
<i>♪ No, no, they can't
take that away from me ♪</i>

694
00:25:42,883 --> 00:25:46,386
<i>♪ No, they can't take that away… ♪</i>

695
00:25:46,470 --> 00:25:48,055
What are you doing, Papa?

696
00:25:48,139 --> 00:25:50,391
Yes, Abe, please tell me
you didn't bring homework.

697
00:25:50,475 --> 00:25:54,520
This is my Catskills
alcohol-consumption index.

698
00:25:54,604 --> 00:25:57,566
I drink more up here,
but I've devised a system

699
00:25:57,650 --> 00:25:59,651
to keep from getting tipsy.

700
00:25:59,735 --> 00:26:02,654
Takes into account food
consumption, time frame,

701
00:26:02,738 --> 00:26:04,406
total alcohol intake.

702
00:26:04,490 --> 00:26:07,160
Here, verify this for me.

703
00:26:07,244 --> 00:26:09,871
Drink number one: a Napoleon, 7:30.

704
00:26:09,955 --> 00:26:12,582
Napoleon reported for duty at 7:30.
Check.

705
00:26:12,666 --> 00:26:15,418
Drink number two: a Tom Collins, 8:15.

706
00:26:15,502 --> 00:26:18,088
Tom Collins made the list at 8:15.

707
00:26:18,172 --> 00:26:19,798
Now it's 9:15,

708
00:26:19,882 --> 00:26:21,592
and I'm just finishing my gin rickey

709
00:26:21,676 --> 00:26:24,178
with absolutely no
sign of "abbleebliation."

710
00:26:24,262 --> 00:26:26,598
I'm sorry. No sign of what?

711
00:26:26,682 --> 00:26:29,017
"Abeebalation."
Why is that so hard to say?

712
00:26:29,101 --> 00:26:31,519
Because you are totally "abeebalated."

713
00:26:31,603 --> 00:26:34,314
<i>♪ Can't take that away ♪</i>

714
00:26:34,398 --> 00:26:39,779
<i>♪ From me ♪</i>

715
00:26:42,824 --> 00:26:45,369
[APPLAUSE]

716
00:26:46,870 --> 00:26:50,582
Ken Washington and his
Swinging Lamplighters, everybody.

717
00:26:50,666 --> 00:26:52,918
