dolled up for if not for him?

951
00:36:13,161 --> 00:36:15,621
She's been playing an
awful lot of tennis lately.

952
00:36:15,705 --> 00:36:18,083
-The tennis pro?
-You said it, not me.

953
00:36:18,167 --> 00:36:20,710
I'm getting tired of people
hopping around from bed to bed.

954
00:36:20,794 --> 00:36:22,462
Tony Curtis, Gladys Lipschitz.

955
00:36:22,546 --> 00:36:24,381
Stay in one place. It's exhausting.

956
00:36:24,465 --> 00:36:26,800
Oh, please.
If my son would just stay with a girl

957
00:36:26,884 --> 00:36:28,427
for more than two dates, I'd plotz.

958
00:36:28,511 --> 00:36:31,389
-Benjamin?
-No one is good enough for him.

959
00:36:31,473 --> 00:36:35,768
Lovely girls from good families.
They cook. They're sweet as pie.

960
00:36:35,852 --> 00:36:38,230
They don't laugh too
loud or talk too loud.

961
00:36:38,314 --> 00:36:40,816
"They're too normal," he says.
"They're boring."

962
00:36:40,900 --> 00:36:42,109
Boring? What's that?

963
00:36:42,193 --> 00:36:43,777
All my friends have grandchildren,

964
00:36:43,861 --> 00:36:46,573
and here I am with
nothing on the horizon.

965
00:36:46,657 --> 00:36:49,409
And he's such a catch.
A doctor, handsome.

966
00:36:49,493 --> 00:36:50,493
He's so handsome.

967
00:36:50,577 --> 00:36:52,203
But he says he wants someone interesting,

968
00:36:52,287 --> 00:36:56,040
someone unique… get this, someone weird.

969
00:36:56,124 --> 00:36:57,668
Weird!

970
00:36:57,752 --> 00:37:00,797
I've got the perfect girl for him.

971
00:37:02,507 --> 00:37:05,551
Mink is the ultimate way for your husband

972
00:37:05,635 --> 00:37:07,762
to say, "I love you."

973
00:37:07,846 --> 00:37:11,558
It's the most popular
fur and will last for years.

974
00:37:11,642 --> 00:37:13,852
Very durable.

975
00:37:13,936 --> 00:37:18,149
Raccoon fur is similar
to mink in that it's durable,

976
00:37:18,233 --> 00:37:22,737
and the color scheme is
unique and stands out in a crowd.

977
00:37:22,821 --> 00:37:25,741
Note this, ladies: it is better to buy

978
00:37:25,825 --> 00:37:29,953
a luxurious raccoon
than a poor-quality mink.

979
00:37:30,037 --> 00:37:34,666
Now, let's talk about coordinating muffs.

980
00:37:34,750 --> 00:37:37,045
Your grandmother called them "mufflers,"

981
00:37:37,129 --> 00:37:40,798
but, ladies, this is not
your grandmother's muff.

982
00:37:40,882 --> 00:37:42,800
♪♪

983
00:37:42,884 --> 00:37:44,887
[WOMEN LAUGHING QUIETLY]

984
00:38:02,448 --> 00:38:04,451
♪♪

985
00:38:06,453 --> 00:38:08,455
-[WORKERS CHATTERING]
-[DISHES CLINKING]

986
00:38:21,552 --> 00:38:24,264
-Hey!
-Yeah?

987
00:38:24,348 --> 00:38:26,266
Don't be picking off my plates.

988
00:38:26,350 --> 00:38:28,142
Employee mess is around the corner.

989
00:38:28,226 --> 00:38:30,979
-Grab what you want.
-Thanks.

990
00:38:33,649 --> 00:38:35,567
♪♪

991
00:38:35,651 --> 00:38:37,653
[LIVELY CHATTER NEARBY]

992
00:39:03,265 --> 00:39:05,267
[DOOR CREAKS]

993
00:39:07,770 --> 00:39:09,772
[WOMEN LAUGHING, CHATTERING]

994
00:39:13,693 --> 00:39:15,320
[CHATTER STOPS]

995
00:39:15,404 --> 00:39:17,780
You in plumbing?

996
00:39:17,864 --> 00:39:19,574
-Uh, yeah.
-Need a bunk?

997
00:39:19,658 --> 00:39:22,161
-Yes, I do.
-That one's free.

998
00:39:22,245 --> 00:39:24,497
-Huh?
-Yeah.

999
00:39:31,713 --> 00:39:33,131
Long day?

1000
00:39:33,215 --> 00:39:35,843
Uh, plunged my ass off.

1001
00:39:42,058 --> 00:39:44,060
[BIRDS CALLING]

1002
00:39:45,520 --> 00:39:47,522
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

1003
00:39:49,607 --> 00:39:52,444
Okay, well, I thought spotting
that rose-breasted grosbeak

1004
00:39:52,528 --> 00:39:55,447
would be the highlight of
our day, but I was wrong.

1005
00:39:55,531 --> 00:39:57,366
That's the Bicknell thrush.

1006
00:39:57,450 --> 00:39:59,368
And, folks, this is a rare opportunity

1007
00:39:59,452 --> 00:40:01,371
to hear its beautiful morning song.

1008
00:40:01,455 --> 00:40:03,206
Let's listen.

1009
00:40:03,290 --> 00:40:05,541
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

1010
00:40:05,625 --> 00:40:07,377
[QUIETLY] He's an accomplished surgeon.

1011
00:40:07,461 --> 00:40:09,879
Lenox Hill.
First in his class at Johns Hopkins.

1012
00:40:09,963 --> 00:40:12,716
Had his choice of residencies
at any hospital he chose.

1013
00:40:12,800 --> 00:40:14,718
He's already invented
new surgical techniques

1014
00:40:14,802 --> 00:40:16,428
that have become the worldwide standard,

1015
00:40:16,512 --> 00:40:18,514
which is a remarkable
feat for such a young man.

1016
00:40:18,598 --> 00:40:20,517
He's widely published
in medical journals.

1017
00:40:20,601 --> 00:40:23,269
Now, I know he sounds a little oddball

1018
00:40:23,353 --> 00:40:25,105
on the surface, but he's just eclectic.

1019
00:40:25,189 --> 00:40:26,898
That's often a symbol of accomplishment.

1020
00:40:26,982 --> 00:40:29,902
John Quincy Adams
kept an alligator as a pet.

1021
00:40:29,986 --> 00:40:31,946
And Benjamin Franklin
took naked air baths.

1022
00:40:32,030 --> 00:40:33,489
Did you know that?

1023
00:40:33,573 --> 00:40:35,574
I wonder if Ida's son
was named after him.

1024
00:40:35,658 --> 00:40:38,327
Oh, that's his name, Benjamin.
Do you like the name Benjamin?

1025
00:40:38,411 --> 00:40:39,704
He's never rented.

1026
00:40:39,788 --> 00:40:41,581
He originally lived in Sutton Place

1027
00:40:41,665 --> 00:40:43,250
had a beautiful view of the bridge.

1028
00:40:43,334 --> 00:40:45,168
But as close as it was to his practice,

1029
00:40:45,252 --> 00:40:47,003
he still found it to be too far.

1030
00:40:47,087 --> 00:40:48,839
His patients are everything to him,

1031
00:40:48,923 --> 00:40:51,300
so he sold the place at a loss.
Can you imagine that?

1032
00:40:51,384 --> 00:40:53,302
He bought a duplex just
a block from the hospital.

1033
00:40:53,386 --> 00:40:55,138
It has views, but not of the bridge.

1034
00:40:55,222 --> 00:40:56,973
So they went out about two hours ago?

1035
00:40:57,057 --> 00:40:58,474
Yes, they do this every day.

1036
00:40:58,558 --> 00:41:00,060
They swim, they leave all their stuff.

1037
00:41:00,144 --> 00:41:01,812
This is my sister's purse.

1038
00:41:01,896 --> 00:41:03,522
She doesn't go anywhere
without her purse.

1039
00:41:03,606 --> 00:41:05,399
Look, they could've swum
to another spot on the lake

1040
00:41:05,483 --> 00:41:06,900
and are taking their time to walk back.

1041
00:41:06,984 --> 00:41:09,988
-Not without telling me.
-Or…

1042
00:41:10,072 --> 00:41:12,407
Kyle, get to the office,
find Pauly, and fill him in.

1043
00:41:12,491 --> 00:41:13,992
-We need boats on the water. Go!
-On it!

1044
00:41:14,076 --> 00:41:15,743
Tell them to call
every resort on the lake

1045
00:41:15,827 --> 00:41:17,745
within a five-mile radius!
This is a red flag alert.

1046
00:41:17,829 --> 00:41:19,081
-[WHISTLE BLOWS]
-[PEOPLE MURMURING]

1047
00:41:19,165 --> 00:41:20,749
He loves the opera.

1048
00:41:20,833 --> 00:41:22,835
I know, I know, you're
not the biggest opera fan.

1049
00:41:22,919 --> 00:41:24,295
But the spectacle alone is entertaining,

1050
00:41:24,379 --> 00:41:26,088
so you should give it a chance.

1051
00:41:26,172 --> 00:41:27,590
The sets are sensational.

1052
00:41:27,674 --> 00:41:29,301
And, yes, sopranos can be very annoying,

1053
00:41:29,385 --> 00:41:30,844
but the orchestra is wonderful.

1054
00:41:30,928 --> 00:41:32,304
He loves Puccini.

1055
00:41:32,388 --> 00:41:34,014
MALE ANNOUNCER [OVER PA]: <i>Red flag alert.</i>

1056
00:41:34,098 --> 00:41:36,808
<i>-I repeat, red flag alert.</i>
-[ALARM WAILING IN DISTANCE]

1057
00:41:36,892 --> 00:41:39,562
Joel

1058
00:41:39,646 --> 00:41:42,732
you saw me in my romper, didn't you?

1059
00:41:42,816 --> 00:41:45,610
Yeah.

1060
00:41:45,694 --> 00:41:48,447
BENJAMIN: Fifteen two, fifteen four,

1061
00:41:48,531 --> 00:41:50,449
fifteen six and a pair is eight.

1062
00:41:50,533 --> 00:41:52,284
Not your lucky day, Golda.

1063
00:41:52,368 --> 00:41:53,911
-Benjamin, right?
-I'm sorry?

1064
00:41:53,995 --> 00:41:55,245
-Ida's son?
-That's the rumor.

1065
00:41:55,329 --> 00:41:56,622
-Get up.
-What?

1066
00:41:56,706 --> 00:41:58,041
We are going to do something together.

1067
00:41:58,125 --> 00:41:59,876
The sooner the better. Get up.

1068
00:41:59,960 --> 00:42:02,253
-I'm a million steps behind.
-I'm Miriam Maisel.

1069
00:42:02,337 --> 00:42:04,088
You say that like I should know it.

1070
00:42:04,172 --> 00:42:05,882
Most people do know me here.

1071
00:42:05,966 --> 00:42:08,719
Eight swimsuit sashes?
Top-seeded badminton champ?

1072
00:42:08,803 --> 00:42:10,930
22 straight years in the Steiner
Fire Safety Captain's Club?

1073
00:42:11,014 --> 00:42:13,724
-Nothing?
-I'm just trying not to laugh here.

1074
00:42:13,808 --> 00:42:15,643
What's going on is not funny.
Now, we have to do

1075
00:42:15,727 --> 00:42:17,354
something together to satisfy
my mother's insatiable desire

1076
00:42:17,438 --> 00:42:19,439
for us to meet before I
tie her to a concrete post

1077
00:42:19,523 --> 00:42:20,857
and throw her in the lake.

1078
00:42:20,941 --> 00:42:22,484
Is she dead before
you tie her to the post,

1079
00:42:22,568 --> 00:42:24,903
or do you tie her to the post
alive and dump her in like that?

1080
00:42:24,987 --> 00:42:26,322
-She's alive.
-There'll be screaming.

1081
00:42:26,406 --> 00:42:28,074
Not with the gag in her mouth.

1082
00:42:28,158 --> 00:42:30,368
-You've thought this through.
-Stand. Start walking.

1083
00:42:30,452 --> 00:42:32,578
I'll admit my mother's mentioned you.

1084
00:42:32,662 --> 00:42:34,705
Our mothers have been
scheming to set us up for days,

1085
00:42:34,789 --> 00:42:36,792
and it will not stop until they
see us doing something together.

1086
00:42:36,876 --> 00:42:38,710
So we'll do something,
tell them we gave it a shot,

1087
00:42:38,794 --> 00:42:40,796
nothing came of it, and
I can get back to my life.

1088
00:42:40,880 --> 00:42:42,464
-And you want to do it now?
-Right now.

1089
00:42:42,548 --> 00:42:43,549
You're not missing a meeting

1090
00:42:43,633 --> 00:42:44,883
of the Steiner Fire Safety Corporal Club?

1091
00:42:44,967 --> 00:42:47,470
Captain, captain.
And we don't meet till Thursday.

1092
00:42:47,554 --> 00:42:48,930
-It's raining.
-It'll pass.

1093
00:42:49,014 --> 00:42:51,516
-If it doesn't?
-We melt.

1094
00:42:51,600 --> 00:42:54,769
Okay. I'm convinced. What do we do?

1095
00:42:54,853 --> 00:42:56,522
-Boating? Really?
-Yes. Yes.

1096
00:42:56,606 --> 00:42:58,148
Let me guess, you're a charter member

1097
00:42:58,232 --> 00:43:00,484
of the Aquatic Maritime
Gunwale Anchor Schooner Society

1098
00:43:00,568 --> 00:43:02,027
-nine years running.
-It's what we're doing.

1099
00:43:02,111 --> 00:43:03,737
BENJAMIN: I'm not a big fan of water.

1100
00:43:03,821 --> 00:43:05,156
But I like the public nature of it.

1101
00:43:05,240 --> 00:43:06,741
It's private, yet on display.

1102
00:43:06,825 --> 00:43:08,743
-Everyone will see us.
-Can't argue with logic.

1103
00:43:08,827 --> 00:43:11,162
My new friend Benjamin
and I would like a boat, please.

1104
00:43:11,246 --> 00:43:12,914
You got it.

1105
00:43:12,998 --> 00:43:15,751
No standing, no rocking,
no rowing past the buoys.

1106
00:43:15,835 --> 00:43:17,587
Thank you, Josh.

1107
00:43:17,671 --> 00:43:19,463
Yes, thank you, Josh.

1108
00:43:19,547 --> 00:43:20,881
[MIDGE CLEARS THROAT]

1109
00:43:20,965 --> 00:43:22,967
One, two, three.

1110
00:43:25,888 --> 00:43:27,222
Happy boating!

1111
00:43:27,306 --> 00:43:28,933
Be safe.

1112
00:43:30,935 --> 00:43:32,520
♪♪

1113
00:43:34,940 --> 00:43:37,275
Perfect. Everyone's already watching us.

1114
00:43:37,359 --> 00:43:39,110
Even with the pétanque
championships going on,

1115
00:43:39,194 --> 00:43:41,362
we're still a pull.

1116
00:43:41,446 --> 00:43:43,197
-Well?
-Yes?

1117
00:43:43,281 --> 00:43:45,284
-Are you going to row?
-No. Are you?

1118
00:43:45,368 --> 00:43:47,286
-No. The boy rows.
-I don't row.

1119
00:43:47,370 --> 00:43:49,079
What do you mean, you don't row?
Everybody rows.

1120
00:43:49,163 --> 00:43:51,040
-Then go ahead and row.
-The boy rows.

1121
00:43:51,124 --> 00:43:52,875
-Not this boy.
-Pick up that oar.

1122
00:43:52,959 --> 00:43:54,252
It was your idea to get into a rowboat.

1123
00:43:54,336 --> 00:43:56,212
-Pick up that oar.
-Really? That tone?

1124
00:43:56,296 --> 00:43:58,214
I might as well be rowing with my mother.

1125
00:43:58,298 --> 00:44:00,091
Well, you could've
suggested something else.

1126
00:44:00,175 --> 00:44:01,551
I'm just going along for the ride here.

1127
00:44:01,635 --> 00:44:03,763
I was perfectly happy playing
cribbage with the bubbes.

1128
00:44:03,847 --> 00:44:05,765
-[LAUGHTER]
-[BAND PLAYING LIVELY MUSIC]

1129
00:44:05,849 --> 00:44:07,851
It's getting sillier.

1130
00:44:10,729 --> 00:44:13,482
-What is that?
-The <i>Steiner Daily Newsletter.</i>

1131
00:44:13,566 --> 00:44:15,984
But we've got to at least
look like we're talking.

1132
00:44:16,068 --> 00:44:17,986
-We are talking.
-You're reading.

1133
00:44:18,070 --> 00:44:21,448
I am trying to stay informed,
and I am loving this new font.

1134
00:44:21,532 --> 00:44:24,285
Well, read something and
I'll pretend that I'm enjoying it.

1135
00:44:24,369 --> 00:44:27,497
"Arthur Rossman would like
to thank all the fellow guests

1136
00:44:27,581 --> 00:44:29,999
who consoled him on the
death of his beloved dog Mogul."

1137
00:44:30,083 --> 00:44:32,836
[LAUGHS]

1138
00:44:32,920 --> 00:44:34,463
You are sick.

1139
00:44:34,547 --> 00:44:36,840
Well, read something
light that I can laugh at.

1140
00:44:36,924 --> 00:44:38,217
"There will be a twilight gathering

1141
00:44:38,301 --> 00:44:39,593
of Holocaust survivors tonight in…"

1142
00:44:39,677 --> 00:44:41,763
Just shut up.

1143
00:44:41,847 --> 00:44:44,475
This is going very well.

1144
00:44:51,064 --> 00:44:52,608
You're supposed to row.

1145
00:44:52,692 --> 00:44:54,151
-I know.
-I don't row.

1146
00:44:54,235 --> 00:44:55,611
That's why you didn't get very far.

1147
00:44:55,695 --> 00:44:57,863
-I know.
-She never asked if I could row.

1148
00:44:57,947 --> 00:45:00,658
Well, Benjamin, thank you
for the very, very little you did

1149
00:45:00,742 --> 00:45:02,285
to get my mother off my back.

1150
00:45:02,369 --> 00:45:04,955
-Don't mention it.
-Are you getting out?

1151
00:45:05,039 --> 00:45:07,208
I'm quite comfortable here, actually.

1152
00:45:14,716 --> 00:45:17,009
SAMUEL: I think the angle's fine, sir.

1153
00:45:17,093 --> 00:45:19,011
ABE: Almost, but not quite.

1154
00:45:19,095 --> 00:45:21,223
Rotate it five degrees counterclockwise.

1155
00:45:21,307 --> 00:45:23,183
-Yes, sir.
-ROSE: What's that, Abe?

1156
00:45:23,267 --> 00:45:24,601
My new drinking index.

1157
00:45:24,685 --> 00:45:26,353
I blew some of the timelines before,

1158
00:45:26,437 --> 00:45:27,980
but this one is going to work.

1159
00:45:28,064 --> 00:45:30,400
So ten degrees is five
degrees in your world?

1160
00:45:30,484 --> 00:45:32,360
What world do you live in, Jimmy?

1161
00:45:32,444 --> 00:45:33,903
SAMUEL: But if it's
close enough, I can always

1162
00:45:33,987 --> 00:45:35,947
help you reposition it any
time during the fireworks.

1163
00:45:36,031 --> 00:45:39,952
[SIGHS] And miss which
fireworks while we're doing that?

1164
00:45:40,036 --> 00:45:43,205
The crackly dragon eggs?
The… The weeping willows?

1165
00:45:43,289 --> 00:45:45,166
The gorgeous crescendo of chrysanthemums?

1166
00:45:45,250 --> 00:45:47,001
-Which ones?
-I'm sorry, I'll get it right.

1167
00:45:47,085 --> 00:45:49,211
-With my help, you'll get it right.
-Hello, Joel.

1168
00:45:49,295 --> 00:45:51,673
Oh, hey. You joining us?
Got a spot on the blanket.

1169
00:45:51,757 --> 00:45:54,509
Nah, I'm a little tired.
Probably just gonna turn in.

1170
00:45:54,593 --> 00:45:56,928
-Your new room working out?
-Yeah, it's great.

1171
00:45:57,012 --> 00:45:58,805
Again, thanks for letting
me stay like that, Rose.

1172
00:45:58,889 --> 00:46:00,308
-It was really nice.
-No problem.

1173
00:46:00,392 --> 00:46:01,893
Good night.

1174
00:46:01,977 --> 00:46:03,644
ABE: Fold it up. Let's just start over.

1175
00:46:03,728 --> 00:46:04,854
We'll start over. Get another blanket.

1176
00:46:04,938 --> 00:46:06,063
All right.

1177
00:46:06,147 --> 00:46:08,107
So, I saw you two from the shore.

1178
00:46:08,191 --> 00:46:09,985
Who? Me and Benjamin?

1179
00:46:10,069 --> 00:46:11,987
-What happened?
-I did what I could.

1180
00:46:12,071 --> 00:46:14,406
I mean, why in the world
wouldn't he pick up a damn oar?

1181
00:46:14,490 --> 00:46:15,741
He just refused.

1182
00:46:15,825 --> 00:46:17,117
-So rude.
-So rude.

1183
00:46:17,201 --> 00:46:18,912
I must say, I was unimpressed.

1184
00:46:18,996 --> 00:46:20,747
-How could you not be?
-Oof.

1185
00:46:20,831 --> 00:46:22,249
ABE: Ah, forget it.

1186
00:46:24,251 --> 00:46:25,960
-[CRICKETS CHIRPING]
-[BIRDS CALLING]

1187
00:46:26,044 --> 00:46:27,962
[LAUGHTER, CHATTER]

1188
00:46:28,046 --> 00:46:29,965
-Papa?
-Yes?

1189
00:46:30,049 --> 00:46:31,509
You're snockered.

